        <div class="cta-sub">Mon–Fri 7am–9pm · Sat Mon–Sat 8am–8pm · Sun closed · Phone answered 24/7</div>
        <hr class="cta-divider" />
        <ul class="cta-detail">
          <li>$89 diagnostic, applied to repair</li>
          <li>90-day warranty on parts &amp; labor</li>
          <li>BHGS #A49573</li>
          <li>Laundry closet access, no damage</li>
          <li>Bosch, Miele, LG, Samsung, Whirlpool</li>
          <li>5-county SoCal coverage</li>
        </ul>
      </aside>
    </div>
  </div>
</section>

<!-- UNIT TYPES -->
<section class="section section-black">
  <div class="container">
    <p class="section-number">02, Unit Types We Service</p>
    <h2 class="section-title">Every stackable configuration in SoCal homes</h2>

    <div class="type-grid">
      <div class="type-card">
        <div class="type-badge">Stacked Pair</div>
        <h3>Stacked Washer + Dryer</h3>
        <p>Separate front-load washer and dryer connected with a stacking kit. Most common in LA laundry closets. Both units are independently repairable. Access from the front for most repairs, stacking kit removal required for some rear components.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="type-card">
        <div class="type-badge">All-in-One</div>
        <h3>Combination Washer/Dryer</h3>
        <p>Single unit that washes and dries in one drum, LG and Samsung combo units are the most common in SoCal. Ventless, uses condenser drying. Smaller capacity, longer cycles. Common in WeHo and Silver Lake studios, downtown Long Beach high-rises, OC small 1-bedrooms, and ADU conversions across all five counties with no room for two units.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="type-card">
        <div class="type-badge">Ventless</div>
        <h3>Heat Pump / Ventless Dryers</h3>
        <p>Bosch, Miele, LG, and Electrolux heat pump dryers, increasingly common in SoCal's new construction and ADU conversions where vent duct installation isn't possible. No external duct required. Different failure modes than vented dryers: heat pump compressor, evaporator coil, condenser, not a standard heating element.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="type-card">
        <div class="type-badge">European</div>
        <h3>European Compact Stackable</h3>
        <p>Bosch, Miele, ASKO, Blomberg, Electrolux compact 24-inch units, common in Beverly Hills and Westside LA condos, Newport Coast and Irvine OC luxury condos, Thousand Oaks and Westlake Village townhomes, and renovated apartments across SoCal. Narrower than standard 27-inch US units. Different parts ecosystem and diagnostic approach. We carry OEM parts for Bosch and source Miele through authorized distributors.</p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>
</section>

<!-- PROBLEMS -->
<section class="section section-gray">
  <div class="container">
    <p class="section-number">03, Common Problems</p>
    <h2 class="section-title">What our technicians fix most often</h2>

    <div class="problems-grid">
      <div class="problem-card">
        <h3>Washer Not Spinning</h3>
        <p>A failed drum bearing, worn shock absorbers, a broken drive belt, or an out-of-balance load sensor. On LG and Samsung front-loads, the drum bearing is the most common long-term failure, it produces a grinding sound before the drum eventually stops. We diagnose before recommending the repair scope.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="problem-card">
        <h3>Washer Not Draining</h3>
        <p>A clogged drain pump filter (most front-loads have an accessible filter at the lower front, often overlooked) or a failed drain pump. Check and clean the filter first, it's the single most common cause of drainage problems and resolves without any parts. If the filter is clear, the pump has failed.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="problem-card">
        <h3>Door Boot Gasket Mold</h3>
        <p>The rubber seal around the front-load washer door accumulates moisture and mold, especially in closed laundry closets without ventilation. LA's mild, moist climate makes this worse than in drier cities. Cleaning with diluted bleach and keeping the door ajar after each cycle prevents it. When mold is deep in the gasket folds, replacement is needed.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="problem-card">
        <h3>Door Latch Failure</h3>
        <p>A front-load door that won't latch, or a washer that won't start because it thinks the door is open. The door latch/lock assembly and the door switch are separate components. We test both before recommending replacement, sometimes the door just needs the latch tab cleaned of detergent buildup.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="problem-card">
        <h3>Dryer Not Heating</h3>
        <p>On vented dryers: check the vent duct first, then the heating element, thermal fuse, and thermistor in that order. On heat pump dryers: the heat pump compressor, refrigerant circuit, or evaporator coil requires a different diagnostic path entirely, we approach these correctly rather than applying vented-dryer logic.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="problem-card">
        <h3>Dryer Takes Too Long</h3>
        <p>A blocked or kinked vent duct behind the stack is the most common cause in laundry closets, moisture can't escape and the dryer runs cycle after cycle without drying. We check the vent duct, vent termination outside the building, and moisture sensor before diagnosing a heating or motor problem.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="problem-card">
        <h3>Loud Noise During Washing</h3>
        <p>Drum bearings wearing out produce a rumbling or grinding sound that worsens over time. Foreign objects (coins, zippers, bra underwires) caught in the drum or pump produce rattling or grinding. Worn shock absorbers or suspension rods produce banging on spin. We identify the specific source before recommending the repair.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="problem-card">
        <h3>Washer Leaking</h3>
        <p>Leaks in front-load stacked units are urgent, water damage to a laundry closet in an apartment can affect the unit below. Common sources: door boot gasket tear, loose drain hose connection, failed water inlet valve. We locate the exact source before doing any work, and treat leaks as priority calls.</p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>
</section>

