    <h2 class="section-title">Why stacked unit repair across SoCal is different from a laundry room job</h2>

    <div class="closet-block">
      <div class="cl-label">🏢 SoCal Condos, Apartments &amp; Tight Spaces</div>
      <h3>Half of SoCal lives with a laundry closet, we know how to work in them</h3>
      <p>West Hollywood, Silver Lake, Culver City, Mid-City, Koreatown, the Wilshire corridor in LA; downtown Long Beach high-rises; Anaheim, Irvine, Costa Mesa OC condos; Thousand Oaks and Westlake Village townhomes; the IE's expanding ADU stock in Rancho Cucamonga, Riverside, and Corona, these are neighborhoods of apartments, condos, and ADUs where the laundry setup is a stacked pair in a 24–30 inch closet opening, sometimes with a bifold door that barely clears the units. When the washer or dryer goes down here, there's no alternative nearby machine and no room to maneuver.</p>
      <p>Most repairs on stacked front-load units can be done from the front without unstacking or moving the units. Door latch, drain pump filter, gasket cleaning, door boot replacement, and many control board swaps all have front access. When rear access is needed, drum bearing replacement, rear drum seal, or vent duct clearing, we know how to safely move a stacked pair in a tight space without scraping walls or cracking floor tiles.</p>

      <div class="cl-grid">
        <div class="cl-item"><strong>Front-access repairs</strong><span>Door latch, drain filter, door boot gasket, control board, most motor work</span></div>
