<!-- RECENT REPAIRS -->
<section class="section section-black">
  <div class="container">
    <p class="section-number">07, Recent Repairs</p>
    <h2 class="section-title">What our technicians actually fixed recently</h2>

    <div class="repairs-grid">
      <div class="repair-card">
        <div class="repair-title">West Hollywood · LG WM3400CW / DLEC888V Stack</div>
        <h3>"Dryer runs all night and clothes still damp"</h3>
        <p>Severely kinked vent duct, the flexible duct behind the stack had been compressed when the units were installed and was running at roughly 20% of its rated diameter. The dryer was producing full heat but moisture had nowhere to go. The dryer had been running this way since installation, likely years before the current tenant.</p>
        <div class="repair-detail">Partially unstacked the dryer to access the vent connection, replaced crushed flexible duct with rigid elbow + short flexible section correctly routed with no kinks. Tested with moisture meter, humidity at vent termination confirmed proper exhausting. Customer noted clothes were dry in one cycle for the first time since moving in.</div>
      </div>

      <div class="repair-card">
        <div class="repair-title">Newport Beach (OC) · Samsung WF45R6100AW / DVE45R6100W</div>
        <h3>"Washer smells terrible, getting worse every week"</h3>
        <p>Severe mold accumulation in the door boot gasket and drum interior of a Newport Beach condo unit. The pair was in a fully enclosed laundry closet with the bifold doors kept closed, no air circulation at any point. SoCal coastal humidity plus a sealed space had created ideal mold conditions. The gasket was deeply contaminated in the fold channels behind the visible surface.</p>
        <div class="repair-detail">Replaced door boot gasket (contamination was too deep for surface cleaning). Ran a drum cleaning cycle with bleach. Advised customer on keeping the door ajar after every wash, leaving the closet doors open when not in use, and running a monthly drum-clean cycle. Mold hasn't recurred in 4 months per follow-up. Coastal installations especially benefit from the door-ajar habit.</div>
      </div>

      <div class="repair-card">
        <div class="repair-title">Beverly Hills · Bosch 800 Series 24" Stack</div>
        <h3>"Washer won't drain, just sits in water"</h3>
        <p>Clogged drain pump filter. The Bosch 800 Series front-load has a filter access panel at the lower front, it's designed to be user-serviceable, but most people don't know it exists. The filter was completely blocked with lint, fabric fibers, and a sock fragment. Zero flow to the drain pump.</p>
        <div class="repair-detail">Cleaned the drain pump filter thoroughly, removed the debris blocking flow. Ran a drain cycle to confirm pump was functional (it was). 20-minute call. Showed customer where the filter is and how to clean it monthly, this is the single most effective maintenance step for any front-load washer, and it's rarely in the owner's manual as prominently as it should be.</div>
      </div>

      <div class="repair-card">
        <div class="repair-title">Thousand Oaks (Ventura) · Miele WCR870 / TWR860 Heat Pump Stack</div>
        <h3>"Dryer shows F and won't finish a cycle"</h3>
        <p>Heat pump dryer fault on a Miele ventless unit in a Thousand Oaks townhome, the F error on this Miele model indicates a heat exchanger blockage or condenser issue. The condenser (which collects moisture from the drum air) had a significant lint buildup that was preventing efficient heat exchange. Miele heat pump dryers have a condenser cleaning indicator that the customer had dismissed as a "maintenance reminder."</p>
        <div class="repair-detail">Removed and thoroughly cleaned the condenser assembly, significant lint accumulation despite only 2 years of use (high-lint household fabrics). Reset the maintenance counter. Dryer completed full cycles without fault code. Explained the condenser cleaning schedule, Miele recommends every 3 months for heat pump models in heavy-use households.</div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>
</section>

